  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Guest House at Wiyuan
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The ancient city once fell to calamity's burning scourge,
    So walls were raised anew beside the river's curve.
    The people sparse, the fences few and far between,
    Stony fields lie barren—half consumed by thistle green.

    Clouds touch the distant passes, mountains wear strange dress,
    As sunset falls on watchtowers, drums urge haste distress.
    I count the days till homeward—yet the road stretches wide,
    And in this exile's longing, sorrow swells with tide.
  footnotes:
    - Wiyuan (渭原) likely refers to a region in the borderlands of ancient China or a place near the Wei River. The poem reflects on the reconstruction of a settlement destroyed by previous conflict or disaster.
    - The 'watchtowers' (譙樓) and 'drums and horns' (鼓角) suggest a military frontier post, emphasizing the poem's setting in a remote, fortified outpost.
